'''Darius I''' ({{lang-peo|êé≠êé†êéºêéπêé∫êé¢êèÅ|translit=DƒÅrayava(h)u≈°}}; [[New Persian]]: {{lang|fa|ÿØÿßÿ±€åŸàÿ¥||translit=DƒÅryu≈°|rtl=yes}}; {{hebrew Name|◊ì÷∏÷º◊®÷∞◊ô÷∏◊ï÷∂◊©◊Å|Dar…ôyave≈°|DƒÅr«ùyƒÅwe≈°}}; c. 550 ‚Äì 486 BCE), commonly known as '''Darius the Great''', was the third [[List of kings of Persia|Persian]] [[King of Kings]] of the [[Achaemenid Empire]], reigning from 522 BCE until his death in 486 BCE. He ruled the empire at its peak, when it included much of [[West Asia]], parts of the [[Caucasus]], parts of the [[Balkans]] ([[Thrace]]-[[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]], and [[Paeonia (kingdom)|Paeonia]]), most of the [[Black Sea]] coastal regions, Central Asia, as far as the [[Achaemenid invasion of the Indus Valley|Indus Valley]] in the far east and portions of north and northeast Africa including [[History of Achaemenid Egypt|Egypt]] (Mudr√¢ya), eastern [[ancient Libya|Libya]], and coastal [[Sudan (region)|Sudan]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/dagestan|title=DƒÄ·∏†ESTƒÄN|access-date=29 December 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=riW0kKzat2sC&amp;q=achaemenid+empire+abkhazia&amp;pg=PA409|title=The Making of the Georgian Nation|access-date=29 December 2014|isbn=978-0253209153|last1=Suny|first1=Ronald Grigor|year=1994}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Darius ascended the throne by overthrowing the legitimate Achaemenid monarch [[Bardiya]], whom he later fabricated to be an imposter named [[Gaumata]]. The new king met with rebellions throughout his kingdom and quelled them each time. A major event in Darius's life was his expedition to punish [[Classical Athens|Athens]] and [[Eretria]] for their aid in the [[Ionian Revolt]] and subjugate [[Ancient Greece|Greece]]. Although ultimately ending in failure at the [[Battle of Marathon]], Darius succeeded in the re-subjugation of [[Thrace]], expansion of the empire through the conquest of [[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|Macedon]], the [[Cyclades]] and the island of [[Naxos]] and the sacking of the city of Eretria.

Darius organized the empire by dividing it into provinces and placing [[satraps]] to govern it. He organized [[Achaemenid coinage]] as a new uniform monetary system, along with making [[Official Aramaic language|Aramaic]] the official language of the empire. He also put the empire in better standing by building roads and introducing standard weights and measures. Through these changes, the empire was centralized and unified.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|title = Worlds Together, Worlds Apart concise edition vol.1|last = Pollard|first = Elizabeth|publisher = W.W. Norton &amp; Company, Inc.|year = 2015|isbn = 978-0-393-25093-0|location = New York|pages = 132}}&lt;/ref&gt; Darius also worked on construction projects throughout the empire, focusing on [[Susa]], [[Pasargadae]], [[Persepolis]], [[Babylon]], and [[Persian Egypt|Egypt]]. He had the cliff-face [[Behistun Inscription]] carved to record his conquests, an important testimony of the [[Old Persian language]].

Darius is mentioned in the [[Hebrew Bible|biblical books]] of [[Book of Haggai|Haggai]], [[Book of Zechariah|Zechariah]], and [[Ezra‚ÄìNehemiah]].

==Etymology==
{{main|Darius (given name)}}
[[File:DNa Inscription DƒÅrayavau≈°.jpg|thumb|left|{{center|The name of [[Darius I]] in [[Old Persian cuneiform]] on the [[DNa inscription]] of [[Tomb of Darius I|his tomb]]: ''DƒÅrayavau≈°'' ({{wikt-lang|peo|êé≠êé†êéºêéπêé∫êé¢êèÅ}})}}]]
{{lang|la|DƒÅrƒ´us}} and {{lang|la|DƒÅrƒìus}} are the [[Latin]] forms of the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] {{lang|grc-Latn|Dare√Æos}} ({{lang|grc|[[wikt:ŒîŒ±œÅŒµ·øñŒøœÇ|ŒîŒ±œÅŒµ·øñŒøœÇ]]}}), itself from [[Old Persian]] {{lang|peo-Latn|DƒÅrayau≈°}} ({{lang|peo|êé≠êé†êéºêéπêé¢êèÅ}}, {{transl|peo|d-a-r-y-u≈°}}), which is a shortened form of ''DƒÅrayava ∞u≈°'' ({{wikt-lang|peo|êé≠êé†êéºêéπêé∫êé¢êèÅ}}, {{transl|peo|d-a-r-y-v-u-≈°}}).{{sfn|Schmitt|1994|p=40}} The longer form is also seen to have been reflected in the [[Achaemenid Elamite|Elamite]] {{lang|elx-Latn|Da-ri-(y)a-ma-u-i≈°}}, [[Late Babylonian|Babylonian]] {{lang|akk-Latn|Da-(a-)ri-ia-(a-)mu≈°}}, [[Imperial Aramaic|Aramaic]] {{lang|arc-Latn|drywhw≈°}} ({{lang|arc|ê°Éê°ìê°âê°Öê°Ñê°Öê°î}}), and possibly the longer Greek form {{lang|grc-Latn|Dareia√Æos}} ({{lang|grc|ŒîŒ±œÅŒµŒπŒ±·øñŒøœÇ}}).{{sfn|Schmitt|1994|p=40}} The name is a nominative form meaning &quot;he who holds firm the good(ness)&quot;, which can be seen by the first part {{lang|peo-Latn|dƒÅraya}}, meaning &quot;holder&quot;, and the adverb {{lang|peo-Latn|vau}}, meaning &quot;goodness&quot;.{{sfn|Schmitt|1994|p=40}}

==Primary sources==
{{see also|Behistun Inscription|DNa inscription|Herodotus}}
{{multiple image
|align         = right
|caption_align = center
|header        = Apadana foundation tablets of Darius the Great 
|total_width   = 400
|image1        = Corner of the Apadana Darius the Great inscription.jpg
|caption1      = Gold foundation tablets of Darius I for the [[Apadana Palace]], in their original stone box. The [[Apadana hoard|Apadana coin hoard]] had been deposited underneath. Circa 510 BC.
|image2        = Deposition plate of Darius I in Persepolis.jpg
|caption2      = One of the two gold deposition plates. Two more were in silver. They all had the same trilingual inscription (DPh inscription).
}}
At some time between his [[coronation]] and his death, Darius left a tri-lingual monumental [[relief]] on [[Mount Behistun]], which was written in [[Elamite]], [[Old Persian]] and [[Akkadian language|Babylonian]]. The inscription begins with a brief autobiography including his [[ancestry]] and [[Lineage (anthropology)|lineage]]. To aid the presentation of his ancestry, Darius wrote down the sequence of events that occurred after the death of [[Cyrus the Great]].{{sfn|Duncker|1882|p=192}}{{sfn|Egerton|1994|p=6}} Darius mentions several times that he is the rightful king by the grace of the supreme deity [[Ahura Mazda]]. In addition, further texts and monuments from [[Persepolis]] have been found, as well as a clay tablet containing an [[Old Persian cuneiform]] of Darius from [[Gherla]], [[Romania]] (Harmatta) and a letter from Darius to Gadates, preserved in a [[Greek language|Greek]] text of the [[Roman period]].{{sfn|Shahbazi|1994|pp=41‚Äì50}}{{sfn|Kuhrt|2013|page=197}}{{sfn|Frye|1984|page=103}}{{sfn|Schmitt|2000|page=53}} In the foundation tablets of [[Apadana Palace]], Darius described in [[Old Persian cuneiform]] the extent of his Empire in broad geographical terms:&lt;ref name=&quot;ACH&quot;&gt;{{cite journal |last1=Zournatzi |first1=Antigoni |title=The Apadana Coin Hoards, Darius I, and the West |journal=American Journal of Numismatics (1989‚Äì) |volume=15 |year=2003 |pages=1‚Äì28 |jstor=43580364 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book |title=Persepolis : discovery and afterlife of a world wonder |date=2012 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/persepolis_discovery_and_afterlife_of_a_world_wonder/page/n195 171]‚Äì181 |url=https://archive.org/details/persepolis_discovery_and_afterlife_of_a_world_wonder |language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt;

{{Quote|''Darius the great king, king of kings, king of countries, son of Hystaspes, an Achaemenid. King Darius says: This is the kingdom which I hold, from the [[Scythians|Sacae]] who are beyond [[Sogdia]] to [[Kingdom of Kush|Kush]], and from [[Sind]] ([[Old Persian]]: [[Wikt:êèÉêé°êéØêé¢êèÅ|êèÉêé°êé≠êé¢êé∫]], &quot;Hidauv&quot;, [[locative]] of &quot;[[Hindush|Hidu≈°]]&quot;, i.e. &quot;[[Indus valley]]&quot;) to [[Lydia]] ([[Old Persian]]: &quot;Spard√¢&quot;) ‚Äì [this is] what [[Ahura Mazda|Ahuramazda]], the greatest of gods, bestowed upon me. May Ahuramazda protect me and my royal house!''|DPh inscription of Darius I in the foundations of the Apadana Palace}}

[[Herodotus]], a Greek historian and author of ''[[Histories (Herodotus)|The Histories]]'', provided an account of many [[Persian people#Ancient history and origin|Persian]] kings and the [[Greco-Persian Wars]]. He wrote extensively on Darius, spanning half of Book 3 along with Books 4, 5 and 6. It begins with the removal of the alleged [[usurper]] [[Gaumata]] and continues to the end of Darius's reign.{{sfn|Shahbazi|1994|pp=41‚Äì50}}

==Early life==
{{multiple image
|align         = right
|caption_align = center
|total_width   = 400
|header        = The predecessor of Darius: Dariya/ Gaumata
|image1        = Gaumata being trampled upon by Darius.jpg
|caption1      = &quot;[[Gaumata]]&quot; being trampled upon by Darius the Great, [[Behistun inscription]]. The [[Old Persian]] inscription reads &quot;This is Gaum√¢ta, the Magian. He lied, saying ''&quot;I am [[Smerdis]], the son of [[Cyrus II|Cyrus]], I am king&quot;''.&quot;&lt;ref name=DB&gt;{{cite book |title=Behistun, minor inscriptions DBb inscription- Livius |url=https://www.livius.org/sources/content/behistun-persian-text/behistun-minor-inscriptions/}}&lt;/ref&gt;
|image2        = Gaumata_portrait_on_the_Behistun_inscription.jpg
|caption2      = Portrait of Achaemenid King [[Bardiya]], or &quot;[[Gaumata]]&quot;, from the reliefs at Behistun (detail).
|footer        = Darius toppled the previous Achaemenid ruler (here depicted in the reliefs of the [[Behistun inscription]]) to acquire the throne.
}}

Darius was the eldest of five sons to [[Hystaspes (father of Darius I)|Hystaspes]].{{sfn|Shahbazi|1994|pp=41‚Äì50}} The identity of his mother is uncertain. According to the modern historian [[Alireza Shapour Shahbazi]] (1994), Darius' mother was a certain Rhodogune.{{sfn|Shahbazi|1994|pp=41‚Äì50}} However, according to Lloyd Llewellyn-Jones (2013), recently uncovered texts in Persepolis indicates that his mother was [[Irdabama]], an affluent landowner descended from a family of local Elamite rulers.{{sfn|Llewellyn-Jones|2013|p=112}} Richard Stoneman likewise refers Irdabama to as the mother of Darius.{{sfn|Stoneman|2015|p=189}} The [[Behistun Inscription]] of Darius states that his father was [[satrap]] of [[Bactria]] in 522 BCE.{{efn|According to [[Herodotus]], Hystaspes was the satrap of [[Fars Province#Persis|Persis]], although the French [[Iranologist]] [[Pierre Briant]] states that this is an error.{{sfn|Briant|2002|p=467}} Richard Stoneman likewise considers Herodotus' account to be incorrect.{{sfn|Stoneman|2015|p=20}}}} According to Herodotus (III.139), Darius, prior to seizing power and &quot;of no consequence at the time&quot;, had served as a spearman (''doryphoros'') in the Egyptian campaign (528‚Äì525 BCE) of [[Cambyses II]], then the Persian Great King;{{sfn|Cook|1985|p=217}} this is often interpreted to mean he was the king's personal spear-carrier, an important role. Hystaspes was an officer in [[Cyrus the Great|Cyrus]]' army and a noble of his court.{{sfn|Abbott|2009|p=14}}

Before Cyrus and his army crossed the [[Aras River]] to battle with the Armenians, he installed his son [[Cambyses II]] as king in case he should not return from battle.{{sfn|Abbott|2009|p=14‚Äì15}} However, once Cyrus had crossed the Aras River, he had a vision in which Darius had wings atop his shoulders and stood upon the confines of Europe and Asia (the known world). When Cyrus awoke from the dream, he inferred it as a great danger to the future security of the empire, as it meant that Darius would one day rule the whole world. However, his son Cambyses was the heir to the throne, not Darius, causing Cyrus to wonder if Darius was forming treasonable and ambitious designs. This led Cyrus to order Hystaspes to go back to [[Persis]] and watch over his son strictly, until Cyrus himself returned.{{sfn|Abbott|2009|p=15‚Äì16}} Darius did not seem to have any treasonous thoughts as Cambyses II ascended the throne peacefully; and, through promotion, Darius was eventually elevated to be Cambyses's personal [[lancer]].

===Accession===
[[File:Lineage of Darius the Great.jpg|thumb|left|Lineage of Darius the Great according to the [[Behistun Inscription]].]]
There are different accounts of the rise of Darius to the throne from both Darius himself and Greek historians. The oldest records report a convoluted sequence of events in which Cambyses II lost his mind, murdered his brother [[Bardiya]], and was killed by an infected leg wound. After this, Darius and a group of six nobles traveled to Sikayauvati to kill an usurper, [[Gaumata]], who had taken the throne by pretending to be Bardiya during the true king's absence.

Darius's account, written at the Behistun Inscription, states that Cambyses II killed his own brother Bardiya, but that this murder was not known among the [[Iranian people]]. A would-be [[usurper]] named Gaumata came and lied to the people, stating he was Bardiya.{{sfn|Boardman|1988|p=54}} The Iranians had grown rebellious against Cambyses's rule and on 11 March 522 BCE a revolt against Cambyses broke out in his absence. On 1 July, the Iranian people chose to be under the leadership of Gaumata, as &quot;Bardiya&quot;. No member of the Achaemenid family would rise against Gaumata for the safety of their own life. Darius, who had served Cambyses as his lance-bearer until the deposed ruler's death, prayed for aid and in September 522 BCE, along with [[Otanes]], [[Intaphrenes]], [[Gobryas]], [[Hydarnes]], [[Megabyzus]] and [[Aspathines]], killed Gaumata in the fortress of Sikayauvati.{{sfn|Boardman|1988|p=54}}

{{multiple image
|header     = Cylinder seal of Darius the Great
|align      = right
